    <!-- First Tattoo Guide -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>First Tattoo Guide</h2>
      <p class="detail-description" style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Choosing the right placement for your first tattoo can make the difference between a manageable and an overwhelming experience. Here's what to consider.</p>

      <div class="rec-grid">
        <div class="rec-card">
          <h4>Best for Beginners</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Outer forearm — low pain, easy to show or cover</li>
            <li>Outer bicep — muscular padding, moderate visibility</li>
            <li>Upper back — large flat area, low sensitivity</li>
            <li>Calf — fleshy, low pain, good for medium pieces</li>
            <li>Outer thigh — large canvas, very tolerable pain</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="rec-card avoid">
          <h4>Avoid for First Tattoo</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Ribs — extremely painful, lots of movement</li>
            <li>Hands / Fingers — high pain, fades quickly</li>
            <li>Sternum / Chest center — bone pain, sensitive</li>
            <li>Feet / Toes — thin skin over bone, hard to heal</li>
            <li>Neck / Head — very visible, very painful</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Pain Management Tips</h3>
      <ul class="tips-list">
        <li><strong>Sleep well the night before.</strong> Fatigue lowers your pain threshold significantly. Aim for 7-9 hours.</li>
        <li><strong>Eat a solid meal 1-2 hours before.</strong> Low blood sugar makes pain worse and can cause dizziness.</li>
        <li><strong>Stay hydrated.</strong> Well-hydrated skin takes ink better and heals faster.</li>
        <li><strong>Avoid alcohol for 24 hours.</strong> Alcohol thins blood, increases bleeding, and can affect ink retention.</li>
        <li><strong>Bring distractions.</strong> Music, podcasts, or a friend to talk to can help your brain process the pain differently.</li>
        <li><strong>Breathe slowly and deeply.</strong> Controlled breathing activates your parasympathetic nervous system and reduces pain perception.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about numbing cream.</strong> Some artists allow topical lidocaine — always ask before applying anything.</li>
        <li><strong>Take breaks when needed.</strong> It's okay to pause during long sessions. Communicate with your artist.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the most painful place to get a tattoo? <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>The most painful tattoo locations include the ribs, sternum, armpit, inner elbow, kneecap, hands, feet, groin, and head/face. These areas have thin skin, high nerve density, or close bone proximity, all of which amplify pain during tattooing.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the least painful place to get a tattoo? <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>The least painful tattoo spots are the outer forearm, outer bicep, upper back, calf, and outer thigh. These areas have thicker skin, more muscle and fat padding, and fewer nerve endings, making the tattooing process more tolerable.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does tattoo pain last after getting inked? <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Acute tattoo pain during the session ends immediately after. Post-tattoo soreness typically lasts 3-7 days, feeling similar to a sunburn. Full skin healing takes 2-4 weeks for most areas, though joints and high-friction zones may take longer. Internal skin layers fully heal in 3-6 months.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does tattoo pain differ between men and women? <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Pain perception varies more between individuals than between genders. Factors like skin thickness, body fat distribution, stress levels, sleep quality, and personal pain tolerance have a much greater impact. Some studies suggest hormonal fluctuations can affect pain sensitivity, so timing your session when you feel well-rested may help.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How can I reduce tattoo pain? <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>To reduce tattoo pain: get plenty of sleep the night before, eat a full meal 1-2 hours before your session, stay hydrated, avoid alcohol and blood thinners for 24 hours prior, use a topical numbing cream (ask your artist first), take breaks during long sessions, and practice slow deep breathing during painful areas. Choosing a less sensitive body area also helps significantly.</p></div>
      </div>
